@startuml
skinparam MinClassWidth 120
skinparam linetype ortho
skinparam packageMargin 20
skinparam nodesep 80
skinparam ranksep 80
title Party Role - Defining Policy (Annotated)

' ===== PARTY BASE =====
package "Core Party Archetype" {
  object Party
  object Person
  object Organization

  Person -up-|> Party
  Organization -up-|> Party
}

' ===== PARTY ROLE =====
package "PartyRole" #FFCCCC {
  object PartyRole {
    partyId: PartyId
    role: Role
  }

  object Role {
    name: String
  }

  object PartyRoleDefiningPolicy {
    canDefineFor(Party, Role): boolean
  }

  PartyRole "1" *-- "1" Role
  Party "1" -- "0..*" PartyRole : plays
  PartyRoleDefiningPolicy ..> Party : validates
  PartyRoleDefiningPolicy ..> Role : checks
}

note right of Role
  <b>Role = String name</b>

  Simple approach:
  - "EMPLOYEE"
  - "EMPLOYER"
  - "CUSTOMER"
  - "MANAGER"

  Flexible but needs validation
  to prevent chaos.
end note

note right of PartyRoleDefiningPolicy
  <b>Policy = Validation Logic</b>

  Validates: "Can this Party play this Role?"

  Implementations:
  - alwaysAllow()
  - requiresPersonOnly()
  - requiresOrganizationOnly()
  - composite(policy1, policy2, ...)

  Example:
  Role("EMPLOYEE") with requiresPersonOnly()
  Organization cannot play EMPLOYEE role

  Same pattern as AddressDefiningPolicy.
end note

note bottom of PartyRole
  <b>String-based approach with Policy</b>

  PartyRole with Role name (String):
  - Simple and flexible
  - No compile-time safety
  - Runtime validation via Policy

  DefiningPolicy pattern used across:
  - AddressDefiningPolicy
  - PartyRoleDefiningPolicy
  - PartyRelationshipDefiningPolicy

  Policy = behavior, multiple implementations
  No Constraint needed (that's for catalog)
end note

@enduml
